The exercise is complete. Conway's Game of Life with an infinite sparse grid was implemented following the full TDD red-green-refactor cycle using the specialized agents, autonomously per experiment mode.

## Summary

**All 7 tests passing**, both expected files present, and `experiment-done.txt` written with `DONE`.

The TDD cycle walked through each rule, one test at a time:

| # | Test | Drove new code? |
|---|------|----------------|
| 1 | Empty input → `[]` | Yes (hardcoded `return []`) |
| 2 | Single cell dies (underpopulation) | Green on arrival |
| 3 | Two cells die (underpopulation) | Green on arrival |
| 4 | Block still life survives | **Yes** — real neighbor-counting + survival logic |
| 5 | Overpopulation (4 neighbors dies) | Green on arrival (inverse of survival) |
| 6 | Reproduction (dead cell, 3 neighbors → alive) | **Yes** — candidate-cell expansion + birth rule |
| 7 | Blinker oscillator (negative coords integration) | Green on arrival |

**Implementation highlights** (`src/game-of-life.ts`):
- Sparse representation — only living cells stored; handles negative coordinates naturally via plain offset arithmetic
- Candidate set = live cells plus their 8 neighbors, de-duplicated via a `"x,y"`-keyed Map
- Each candidate filtered by the four rules: live cells survive on 2–3 neighbors, dead cells born on exactly 3
- Refactoring extracted `sameCell`, `neighborhood`/`offsets`, and `countLiveNeighbors` helpers along the way

A documented but deferred improvement remains noted by the refactor agent: tightening `Cell = number[]` to a `[number, number]` tuple, which the API contract permits but which would touch every signature (out of scope for a single refactor step).
